| Parent Rocks    | Mainly igneous; also metamorphic and sedimentary        |
| Parent Minerals | Feldspar, mica, ferromagnesian minerals, volcanic glass |
| Mineral Type    | Silicate (phyllosilicate)                               |
| Nature          | Mostly secondary minerals                               |
</md></sn><sn><md>### General Properties of Clay Minerals

Clay minerals are extremely `fine-grained`, layered silicate minerals that strongly `influence the physical and chemical behavior` of soils. Their special properties come from their ++small particle size++, ++large surface area++, and ++charged crystal surfaces++.

</md></sn><sn><md>##### Particle Size
Clay minerals have particle sizes `smaller than 2 micrometers`. Because of this extremely fine size, they `stay suspended in water` for a long time, `settle slowly`, and show `colloidal behavior`.

##### Surface Area
They have `very high specific surface area`. <br>
`Kaolinite` has ++low surface area++, <br>
`illite` has ++moderate++, and <br>
`smectite` has ++extremely high surface area++. 

This increases `water retention`, `adsorption`, and `chemical reactivity`.


##### Layered Crystal Structure
Clay minerals are `phyllosilicates`, meaning they consist of `stacked layers` of ++tetrahedral (silica)++ and ++octahedral (alumina or magnesia)++ sheets. The `arrangement` of these sheets determines the `type of clay`, such as <br>
kaolinite (1:1) or <br>
smectite/illite (2:1).

##### Surface Charge and Cation Exchange Capacity
Clay minerals carry a `negative charge` due to isomorphic substitution and broken edges. This gives them the ability to attract and exchange cations.Smectites  have the highest cation-exchange capacity, illite moderate, and kaolinite low.

&gt; **CEC** : Smectites &gt; illite &gt; Kaolinite

##### Water Adsorption and Retention
Clay minerals `retain water` on their surfaces and between layers. This water may be tightly held or loosely attached. Their water retention ability `affects soil moisture, swelling, and shrinkage`.

##### Plasticity
When `mixed with water`, clay minerals `become plastic`. They can be `molded or shaped` and hold their form when dry. 
<br>`Smectite` clays show ++high plasticity++,<br>
while `kaolinite` has ++low plasticity++.

##### Swelling and Shrinkage
Some clay minerals, especially `smectites`, can `absorb water between their layers`, leading to ++swelling when wet++ and ++shrinkage when dry++. Kaolinite, with more rigid layers, shows little to no swelling.

##### Cohesion
Clay particles are `cohesive due to electrostatic forces` and water films around them. This gives clay soils strength and makes them stick together, even when wet.

##### Chemical Reactivity
Clay minerals can `adsorb nutrients, organic molecules, and pollutants` due to their surface charge and large surface area. They participate in nutrient cycling, buffering reactions, and contaminant retention.

##### Color
`Pure` clay minerals are `usually light-colored`. However, `natural` clays may appear ++red, yellow, brown, or gray++ depending on the presence of iron oxides, organic matter, or other impurities.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Summary

